<br>
A grandmaster tailor, just to get a few combines together for a Solstice Robe, has already gone through <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> endless</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> combines, foraging, hunting and purchasing to raise his skill.  I make robes, and I respect the 2500pp price when I get a success.  I average 1.5 robes every 46 combines.  What does that entail?  <br>
<br>
I collect 280 spider silks to make 140 swatches.<br>
<br>
I purchase 140 emeralds (15pp ea) and have them imbued.<br>
<br>
I purchase 280 Celestial Solvents, and 280 Scent of Marr.  I combine these to create 280 Celestial Essence.<br>
<br>
I combine 140 Celestial Essence and 140 Imbued Emeralds with 140 Jars of Acid — yield &lt;=140 Blessed Dust of Tunare (considering failures) <br>
<br>
I then combine 140 Blessed Dust of Tunare with 140 Silk Swatches — &lt;=140 Sacred Swatches (consideing failures)<br>
<br>
Finally, I combine the Worked Silver Chain with 3 Sacred Swatches and a pattern.  After all that, I am lucky to get one robe at 200 skill.  This doesn't take into account the cost to have the Chains made by a GM jeweler.  At least they are returned on failure.  the GM jewler I had create my 10 chains failed 4 times at 250 skill...<br>
<br>
That's around <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1500+</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> clicks of my mouse, not counting miscues and moving all this stuff from bag to bag, etc.<br>
<br>
So...besides the fact that it took me a god only knows how many hours to level past 160 in tailoring, it takes an astronomical amount of time, effort and money to create the items.  <br>
<br>
Think about that the next time you purchase something from a tailor.<br>
<br>
PS<br>
I started making Robes at skill 195.  I have gained only 3 points off of them and have done the aforementioned routine at least 7 times.  Tailoring takes great patience, I assure you.  Past 160 it's a living hell...believe me. <p><center>


